segments.text: First of all, Mr. Kerbo, would you tell us something about your early life?
Include the names of your parents, places and dates of their birth and death, the place where you were born and the date of your birth, and the schools you attended before you came to Texas A&M.
My father was born in Georgia in 1856, and
It was in a rural community.
I don't know of any large town there, but it was in the area to the northeast of Atlanta somewhere because I recall hearing him talk, speak of
Being on the edge of Sherman's march to the sea, he saw and heard some of the soldiers coming and going during that time.
And his name was H.C. Harrison C. Kerbo.
Several of the, he, his father and several families of the Curbos came to northeast Texas along about 1867 and settled in Red River County.
Later on, they moved to, some of them moved over into Delta County, close to Cooper, Texas.
That is where I was born in 1895.
My mother also was born before the Civil War.
She was born in 1860 in Octobahaw County, Mississippi.
And her family also came to Texas long about that time and settled in the
area somewhere around where Sherman now is, whatever county that might be.
And later they also moved to Delta County.
In 1900, my father sold out his business in Delta County and moved to West Texas in Fisher County.
raised some livestock and did a little farming and had a general merchandise country store and post office about 20 miles west of Stamford and 20 miles from Robie.
It was quite an isolated country, territory in those days.
Then in 1905,
The family moved to Clarendon, Texas when I was about 10 years old.
And I went through grade high school in Clarendon, Texas, and then went from there to Texas A&M.
How did you make the move first to the vicinity of Stanford?
I beg your pardon?

how how was the move made from east texas to stamford it was made by uh it was made by a train with a chartered car to carry livestock and household goods and so on and then by wagon to be placed west of stamford over in fisher county then in the move from
Fisher County to Clarendon was made in with a wagon and Surrey and then also a chartered car to carry household goods and so on.
We went through in a wagon and Surrey covered wagon.
Must have been quite an experience for a ten-year-old boy.
Well yes, however I had another experience

Prior to that, when we were living in Fisher County, and I was about seven, I guess, years old, along about 1902, I suppose it was, our family, the younger children in our family and two other families with children, decided to have a vacation trip up across the plains, wagon, covered wagon trip.
And we did, and that was quite an experience.
And I remember Lubbock particularly because I never had seen so many windmills in one place in all my life as they were here.
And I recall watering our livestock, horses, going with my father to water those at a stock trough.
I believe by the courthouse, the old courthouse, wherever that was.
It was in Lubbock?
Here in Lubbock.
We camped somewhere off outside the city.
By today's standards, one would hardly think of a trek across the plains by wagon as a vacation.
No, I guess not.
But it was lots of fun for we kids.
We had no cares at all.
What factors were involved in your decision to go to Texas A&M as opposed to, say, some other school?
I think one thing was I understood that it didn't cost as much as some other schools.
And also there was a man named Sawyer who was, I believe, an 1870-some-odd graduate or student.
at A&M who lived in the country.
And his son, several years older than I, had gone there also.
And another boy named Edwin Patterson and myself decided we would go down and become electrical engineers.
We'd been fooling around with radio and the old
dot dash sort of stuff and thought that we'd go down there and become electrical engineers.
He did, but I didn't.
I noted that you were in architecture.
Yes.
I switched to architecture after my first year and found out that there was so much math in the regular engineering course.
What procedures did you go through to enter Texas A&M?

we got a catalog and found out how many units I believe they called it in those days of high school work you had to have to enter and I believe I just barely had enough because we we only had 11 grades in high school at that time and I recall going to
the superintendent of our high school and asking him to support me in my efforts to go there, and he did.
Yeah, I think he wrote a letter or something like that.
Our high school wasn't the best in the world, I guess, but maybe we learned some things that they don't learn now.

I believe there was a period, and it probably was during the time that you entered A&M, that there were schools that were so-called affiliated with A&M, and if you completed one of those, then you could be accepted without an entrance exam.
Well, I did not take an entrance exam, but I don't know whether we were affiliated or not.
But anyway, the letter that he wrote, I got entrance there.
There weren't so many students trying to go there then.
What were your first reactions to Texas A&M and to what there was of the community of College Station when you arrived?
I hardly know.
Of course, I was lonesome.
I was barely 17 years old.
And there was a little hazing going on even before registration.
like pushing a cart with the trunks for the old boys up from the station.
And I was a little bit disturbed, I think, long about that time.
So there were some upperclassmen who arrived, I presume, on the same train with you?
On the same train with myself.
Were there any people there to meet the train when it arrived?
I don't believe so.
Perhaps they might have been, but I just don't recall that.
But a boy named Horace Sawyer was a freshman coming in, and I believe he's one of your distinguished men of the school now, and a boy named E.B.
Patterson, who is now dead, the three of us.
And then there were several older students, former students, old students, arrived on the same train, and we got a little hazing on the train itself, I believe.
We had to do a little singing for them, such as that, but that was all right.
Okay.
Then did you arrive, say, one day and register the next?
I don't recall, just...
I presume fairly quickly after you arrived there you were assigned to or selected a military unit.
Did you have any choice in which unit you entered?
I don't believe I had a choice.
Actually, I had no reason to prefer one over another, and I was assigned to Company K.
Company K was housed in Milner Hall, which was one of the real new halls at that time.

So then if you were in the new hall as a fish, then you didn't have to go through the procedure of carrying water and wood and so forth for the upperclassmen that some of the boys who lived in the older dorms did.
No, I didn't.
We didn't have that problem in Milner Hall.
I lived in the basement.
for the first few months until they put all the attendants down.
So many of them went home.
Then I got to move up to another floor.
But I did live in Foster Hall where we had wood stoves and wooden water problems later on.

at that time why it was just a matter of pitching our bucket out the window hollering at a fish and pitching the bucket out and having him bring the water up and wood what year was that that you lived in foster uh let's see it was the my fourth year that had been uh i went there in 12 i guess that was in
Okay.
Well then, did you live in any dorms other than Milner and Foster then?
In Leggett.
In my last year there, I lived in Leggett Hall.
And that was another one of the fairly new... Another one of the fairly new schools.
I believe Mitchell at that time was the newest, newest hall.
I believe you said your first year you were in K Company.
Were you all, did you...
serving in different companies other than K?
Well I was in K for the first two years I believe.
Then I was assigned to Company E but I still lived in Milner the third year.
Fourth year I was a
half junior, half senior, so I wasn't assigned to any particular unit, as I recall.
And the fifth year, I was Edson of one of the battalions.
I believe, according to the yearbook, it was the 1st Battalion, the 2nd Regiment.
I believe so.
Okay.
Would you describe a typical day
during the time that you were there?
Well, of course, Reveille and the dressing and trying to make Reveille formation on time to march down to the hall and tying the necktie on the run and that sort of thing.
I presume wrapping your leggings
No, at that time, we didn't have the... You didn't have the wrap leggings.
We didn't have the wrap leggings.
We had the old gray uniform.
In fact, all the time I was there, that was our uniform.
And... That's right.
Of course, making Reveille...
then marching to our meals and then going to classes.
If it was muddy, how the old sticky soil would boil up on your heels and your shoes and so on.
Yeah, there were no sidewalks.
No sidewalks.
We had gravel, supposedly gravel sidewalks, but, you know, in wet weather like we have down there, why?
Any boardwalks?
No, we didn't have any boardwalks that I recall.
Seen a few pictures that had some that I think primarily they were around the professor's homes, though.
Perhaps, perhaps so.
What did you do for entertainment and recreation?
Well, there really wasn't any.
Of course, we played baseball in season, and we played a little football in season.
I mean, I was not large enough to play football, and I couldn't hit well enough to play varsity baseball, but I could play company football and baseball and basketball.
although we knew very little about basketball then.
It was on outside courts, dirt, cinder.
Where were those courts, do you remember?
No, they were scattered around over two or three places because two companies would go together to form a team, like I and K companies.
We had our baseball team.
Would this be in all sports then?
In all the sports, you had two companies go together to form a team.
Yes, at that time, yes.
And there really, there wasn't any particular entertainment.
We'd try to get to go to Bryan on occasion if we could get a permit to do that.
We had to get a permit in the first year or two that I was there, as I recall.
It could be denied or it could be approved by the commandant or the assistant commandant.
And it had to be exactly correctly done or it would be disapproved.
And then there were other limitations on going to Brown Financial.
I guess that affects all students.
It doesn't seem to affect too many of them today.
Well, perhaps not now.
Some of them only have two cars now on the local campus here.
You said, I believe earlier, that you lived in
two of the newer dormitories and one of the older ones.
What was life like in those dormitories?
Was it pretty hectic or was it pretty well controlled?
It was pretty well controlled.
Of course it was during study hours in particular, but there were lots of, except during study hours, there were lots of bull sessions that students would gang up in one room

swap stores and tell lies that about what all they had done I suppose but during during after called quarters everything was in everyone was in the military department at that time after called quarters and until
tattoo which I believe came at I don't recall 10 15 perhaps why things were pretty quiet.
Did you have a student patrolling the hallways?
Students walking post in the hallways yes and I have had to walk some posts in there in fact
I don't suppose you have ever seen old Pfeiffer Hall.
The only pictures of it.
It was, I recall, a walking post there because the floor, every step you took by the floor creaked.
So then you had to walk post in a dormitory in which you did not live.
Oh yes, yes.
If you were assigned a post, just like you would be in the service during
Did you ever have to walk post in your own dormitory?
I don't recall that I ever did.
In fact, I believe only the first year that I had to walk post.
I don't recall having to walk post other than the first year.
Was it always just the freshmen who walked the post?
You know, I don't recall.
Or did they discontinue the practice after that?
Well, no, they didn't discontinue the practice, I don't believe, while I was there.
They did discontinue the practice of requiring a written permit to visit Brown because that only lasted about a year after I got there, I believe, or so.
Did the students, in addition to the bull sessions, did they play games in the dorms, rooms, like dominoes or cards or anything of that nature?
I don't remember that they did.
I don't believe so.
I believe at one point there were rules that forbade the cards on campus.
I think so.
I think so.
Also cigarettes.
How about cigars and chewing tobacco?
Cigars, I believe, were not allowed.
Chewing tobacco was not ruled out because I recall I did a little cartooning while I was there.

for the battalion, and I made a strip like mutton, Jeff, and I believe one of them asked the other for a cigarette, and he didn't have any cigarettes, but he had some Star Navy, and it was cheaper anyway.
And that was a popular brand at the time?
Star Navy tobacco, oh yes, it was very popular.
But actually, there was some cigarette smoking going on, although not too many boys.
Was that a serious punishable offense if you were caught?
Yes, it was, but I don't recall what the amount of punishment was.
As a matter of fact, you got, I believe they call it rams.
You got rammed for lots of things.
I spent some time on the
campus working around on the grounds, working off demerits.
So you would work off your demerits that way rather than marching in the bullring or something?
I never did have to march.
I don't, I believe that came along after.
I see.
But I did do some work for the grounds.
What was the food like?
food was good, but wholesome.
Not always very tasty, but it was something that I suppose they still gripe about.
We griped about it, but it was all right.
Did it get pretty monotonous at times?
Yes, it did.
And of course, we had all kinds of names for various things, which I wouldn't do to write up.
But at Speza Hall, we had Mexican waiters at that time, didn't have any student waiters.
And the freshmen

had to sit in the middle of the table, his long table, usually with a senior at each end and... Juniors and sophomores... Juniors and sophomores according to rank on down towards the middle and the freshmen of course in the middle.
I have eaten some
When I was a freshman, I have eaten some parts of my meal under the table for violating some...
The upperclassmen would put you under the table.
Yes, yes.
I guess all of us about that time did.
Did the upperclassmen have various devious means of obtaining your dessert or your kush at that point?
Oh, yes.
Yeah, they'd talk about how...
They'd give it some description that you just
that would tend to turn your stomach, and you didn't want any kush.
I've had that done, too.
However, I developed pretty good resistance to that, because I liked kush.
Did the upperclassmen have any privileges that were not accorded to the freshmen?
Oh, yes, but I don't recall what they were.
Yes, sure, the upperclassmen had lots of privileges that the freshmen didn't have.
I presume that ability of doing a little hazing was one.
Oh, yes, yes.
However, hazing was never a real problem because I noticed that the upperclassmen
didn't haze freshmen whom they didn't like personally.
And of course, the freshmen, we, at least I did, and I guess some of the others did, we used to tease the upperclassmen or kid them about how weak they were when they hit us with a broom or a belt.
We'd ask them if that was as hard as they could hit, and of course,
That brought it on a little more severely.
But hazing was not a problem.
I imagine it would be a problem only for those who sort of took offense to it.
Yes, and not too many of them did that because, as I said, the upperclassmen didn't haze students that they didn't like.
Was it primarily confined to an individual company?
I mean, the upperclassmen in Company K, Hayes only, the freshmen in K?
That's right.
They didn't cross company lines?
No, I don't recall any crossing of lines, company lines.
In fact, I presume that as upperclassmen, we wouldn't have liked it for somebody in another dormitory or another company to invade our company.
That was sacred ground wasn't it?
Yes it was.
Did the cadet officers enjoy any particular privileges over above the other cadets?
Yes.
I don't recall just what all privileges we had.
We could visit during study hours when we were
seniors.
We didn't have to go to chapel if we didn't want to.
And we could want unless we were company officers.
And some of those could wander down to the mess hall without marching with the company.
This would be the regimental staff.
Well, the regimental staff and of course, the
At meal time, certain meal time, the seniors did not have to march to the mess hall.
They could walk down.
If someone was there to take the company down, say.
So primarily if, what, you'd have one of the sergeants?
Perhaps march the company down.
Maybe one officer or the first sergeant, and the rest of them could do as they wanted.
How often was chapel?
You said they could escape chapel occasionally.
The seniors could escape chapel any time, as I recall.
The rest of the students were marched to chapel, and of course, some of them escaped by dodging around back in Foster Hall or Ross Hall or some of those.
And dropping out of formation and scooting around the corner.
Oh, yes, drop out of formation.
Was this only on Sunday that you had chapel, or was it more frequently?
No, it's Sundays.
Did you have any?
It was required that we go to chapel.
but it was required that you go, but apparently they didn't check roll.
No, no, nobody would tell them.
Did you have any favorite instructors while you were there?
Yes, yes, I did.
I had a number of favorites.
Tell us about them.
Well, D.B.
Cofer was one whom I became acquainted with first.
I recall the first time our class was in his classroom, on the board we saw the most perfect script that you can imagine.
